  "meta": {
    "title": "Exercise seed graph — anchored to current PPL routine (Planet Fitness)",
    "spec_version": "aligns with fitness-agent-spec v0.3",
    "purpose": "Portable seed for the exercise graph. Each node = one exercise, tagged so the app can query substitutions (same movement_pattern + overlapping muscles + available equipment), count volume per muscle, and enforce balance. Hand-tagged for correctness; format is schema-agnostic so Claude Code can ingest into whatever tables it scaffolds.",
    "emphasis_convention": "primary muscle = 1.0; meaningful secondary = 0.5; minor secondary = 0.3. Used for fractional set-counting.",
    "load_type_values": ["free_weight", "bodyweight", "smith", "cable", "machine_selectorized", "plate_loaded"],
    "portable_rule": "free_weight & bodyweight = true (loads transfer across gyms); smith/cable/machine = false (context-bound, track per machine_id).",
    "notes": [
      "SETS/REPS ARE INTENTIONALLY OMITTED — those are prescribed by the programming engine, not stored on the exercise node.",
      "BACK CAUTION: exercises tagged affected_structures:['lumbar_spine'] are the ones to watch / swap first given the user's minor back discomfort. Deadlift is the highest spinal-load movement in the routine.",
      "PF REALITY: standard Planet Fitness has NO loadable barbell or rack. 'Free-weight' squat/deadlift here = dumbbell or Smith. Smith bar ≈ 15-20 lb (counterweight), not 45 — its loads don't transfer to a real barbell.",
      "DUMBBELL CAP ≈ 75 lb at PF — pressing/rowing may hit the ceiling eventually; substitutions note machine fallbacks.",
      "ABS feed core volume; CARDIO is conditioning-only (not in per-muscle volume math).",
      "ASSUMPTIONS I made (confirm if wrong): 'weight calf raises' = standing dumbbell or Smith calf raise; 'weight incline bench' = dumbbell or Smith incline (no free barbell at PF); 'free-weight deadlift' = dumbbell/Smith RDL-style, not a floor barbell deadlift.",
      "SUBSTITUTIONS listed as {name, equipment, load_type, when} are candidate pointers; a few reference exercises not yet fully specced as their own nodes — Claude Code can promote them to full nodes when it expands the graph."
    ]
  },

